Note
Route Parameters Not Updating? Here’s Why!
Sometimes you’ll notice this behavior in Angular:(in 1st way)
You are on:
/student/101Now click a link to:
/ student/102The URL changes, but the displayed data doesn’t update.
Why does this happen?
Angular reuses the same component when navigating to the same route with different parameters.
For example:
/student/101
↓
/student/102Both URLs use the same route:
path: 'student/:id'Since the component is already loaded, Angular doesn’t create a new component. It only changes the route parameter.
The Problem
If you use:
this.studentId = this.route.snapshot.paramMap.get('id')!;snapshot reads the parameter only once when the component is created.
So when the parameter changes later, studentId is not updated.
Why?
The constructor runs only once.
constructor(private route: ActivatedRoute) {
this.studentId = this.route.snapshot.paramMap.get('id')!;
}When moving from /student/101 to /student/102:

• ✅ URL changes

• ✅ Same component is reused

• ❌ Constructor does not run again

• ❌ snapshot is not updated
Solution
Instead of snapshot, subscribe to paramMap.
constructor(private route: ActivatedRoute) { this.route.paramMap.subscribe(params => {
this.studentId = params.get('id')!;
});
}
Now, whenever the route parameter changes, Angular automatically updates studentId.
How does subscribe() work?
The constructor still runs only once.
Inside the constructor, subscribe() registers a callback with Angular.
Whenever the route parameter changes, Angular automatically calls that callback.
Think of it like this:
Constructor Runs
│
▼
subscribe() Registers Callback
│
▼
Constructor Finishes
│
▼
Route Parameter Changes
│
▼
Angular Executes CallbackReal-World Example 1: YouTube Subscription
Imagine you subscribe to a YouTube channel.

• You click Subscribe only once.

• Whenever a new video is uploaded, YouTube automatically notifies you.
You don’t subscribe again every time a new video is uploaded.
subscribe() works the same way.
Real-World Example 2: Doorbell
Think of installing a doorbell.

• Installing the doorbell = Constructor runs once.

• Someone presses the bell = Route parameter changes.

• Bell rings every time = Angular calls the subscribed callback.
You install the bell only once, but it keeps notifying you whenever someone presses it.
snapshot vs subscribe()

• snapshot → Reads the route parameter only once.

• subscribe() → Registers a callback once, and Angular calls it every time the route parameter changes.
This is why subscribe() is the recommended approach when navigating between URLs that use the same component with different route parameters.
